<!-- Begin Title -->
<h1>Convolution</h1>
<!-- End Title -->
<hr class=3D"margin-t-1-8 margin-b-3-4">
<!-- Begin Total Content -->
<div class=3D"attachments text-align-r">
<a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/notebooks/IntegralTransforms/Convo=
lution.nb" download=3D"Convolution.nb"><img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfra=
m.com/images/entries/download-notebook-icon.png" width=3D"26" height=3D"27"=
 alt=3D"DOWNLOAD Mathematica Notebook"><span>Download
 <span class=3D"display-i display-n__600">Wolfram&nbsp;</span>Notebook</spa=
n></a>
</div>
<!-- Begin Content -->
<div class=3D"entry-content">
<p>
A convolution is an integral that expresses the amount of overlap of one fu=
nction <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Convoluti=
on/Inline1.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:=
100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"10" height=3D"21" alt=3D"g"> as it is shifted o=
ver another function
 <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Convolution/Inl=
ine2.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" =
border=3D"0" width=3D"12" height=3D"21" alt=3D"f">. It therefore "blends" o=
ne
 function with another. For example, in synthesis imaging, the measured dir=
ty map
 is a convolution of the "true" CLEAN map with the dirty beam (the <a href=
=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/FourierTransform.html">Fourier
 transform</a> of the sampling distribution). The convolution is sometimes =
also known
 by its German name, <i>faltung</i> ("folding").
</p>
<p>
Convolution is implemented in the <a href=3D"http://www.wolfram.com/languag=
e/">Wolfram Language</a> as <tt><a href=3D"http://reference.wolfram.com/lan=
guage/ref/Convolve.html">Convolve</a></tt>[<i>f</i>,
 <i>g</i>, <i>x</i>, <i>y</i>] and <tt><a href=3D"http://reference.wolfram.=
com/language/ref/DiscreteConvolve.html">DiscreteConvolve</a></tt>[<i>f</i>,
 <i>g</i>, <i>n</i>, <i>m</i>].
</p>
<p>
Abstractly, a convolution is defined as a product of functions <img src=3D"=
https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Convolution/Inline3.svg" cla=
ss=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" =
width=3D"12" height=3D"21" alt=3D"f"> and <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wol=
fram.com/images/equations/Convolution/Inline4.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" =
style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"10" height=
=3D"21" alt=3D"g">
 that are objects in the algebra of <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.co=
m/SchwartzFunction.html">Schwartz functions</a>
 in <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Convolution/=
Inline5.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100=
%" border=3D"0" width=3D"19" height=3D"21" alt=3D"R^n">. Convolution of two=
 functions <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Convo=
lution/Inline6.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-wi=
dth:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"12" height=3D"21" alt=3D"f"> and <img src=
=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Convolution/Inline7.svg"=
 class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D=
"0" width=3D"10" height=3D"21" alt=3D"g"> over a finite range <img src=3D"h=
ttps://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Convolution/Inline8.svg" clas=
s=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" w=
idth=3D"36" height=3D"21" alt=3D"[0,t]"> is given by
</p>
<div>
<table summary=3D"" width=3D"100%" align=3D"center" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0" style=3D"padding-left: 50px">
<tbody><tr><td align=3D"left"><img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/ima=
ges/equations/Convolution/NumberedEquation1.svg" class=3D"numberedequation"=
 style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"214" height=
=3D"40" alt=3D" [f*g](t)=3Dint_0^tf(tau)g(t-tau)dtau, "></td><td align=3D"r=
ight" width=3D"3">
<div id=3D"eqn1" class=3D"eqnum">
(1)
</div>
</td></tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
<p>
where the symbol <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations=
/Convolution/Inline9.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;=
max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"67" height=3D"21" alt=3D"[f*g](t)">
 denotes convolution of <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/eq=
uations/Convolution/Inline10.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-heig=
ht:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"12" height=3D"21" alt=3D"f">
 and <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Convolution=
/Inline11.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:1=
00%" border=3D"0" width=3D"10" height=3D"21" alt=3D"g">.
</p>
<p>
Convolution is more often taken over an infinite range,
</p>
<div class=3D"table-responsive-noborders">
<table align=3D"center" width=3D"100%" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" =
style=3D"padding-left: 50px" border=3D"0">
<tbody><tr style=3D""><td align=3D"right" width=3D""><img src=3D"https://ma=
thworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Convolution/Inline12.svg" class=3D"dis=
playformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D=
